DATASET CREATION AND INTEGRATION¶

The datasets include

  • counties.csv, which contains the list of counties in Michigan, along with locations of their nearby weather stations.
  • michigan.csv, which contains the daily covid-19 cases reported for each county in Michigan, downloaded from https://www.michigan.gov/documents/coronavirus/Cases_and_Deaths_by_County_and_by_Date_of_Symptom_Onset_or_by_Date_of_Death2021-10-20_738873_7.xlsx
  • mobility.csv, which contains Apple mobility trends report downloaded from https://covid19.apple.com/mobility.
  • weather.csv. which contains daily weather data downloaded from https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/cdo-web/search?datasetid=GHCND

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

class CountyData:
    def __init__(self, counties, stations):
        """
         A constructor function to initialize the state of the object. You will need to store the following
         variables: list of counties and their associated weather stations, number of daily cases per county,
         relative volume for each mobility pattern (driving, walking, and transit), and their daily weather 
         information (precipitation, maximum and minimum temperature). You may use the following local variables
         to store the data. You only need to store the data from March 1, 2020 to October 17, 2021 for each 
         variable. 
        """ 

        self.counties = counties     # variable to store list of counties in Michigan
        self.stations = stations       # variable to store list of weather stations associated with the counties
        
    def loadCasesData(self, covidFile):
        """
         Function to load the number of confirmed daily Covid19 cases for the different counties from 
         the given input filename. You should use the Case status column to distinguish the confirmed 
         from the probable cases. You may use the pandas DataFrame object named self.cases to store the 
         number of cases for each county. The rows of the data frame should correspond to the different
         days while the columns are the counties. You should store only the data from March 1, 2020
         to October 17, 2021.
        """     
        covidData = pd.read_csv(covidFile)
        confirmed_covidData = covidData[covidData[covidData.columns[2]] == "Confirmed"]
        confirmed_covidData['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(confirmed_covidData['Date'], format='%m/%d/%Y')
        confirmed_covidData = confirmed_covidData[confirmed_covidData['COUNTY'].isin(self.counties)]
        confirmed_covidData = confirmed_covidData.loc[(confirmed_covidData['Date'] >= '3/1/2020') & (confirmed_covidData['Date'] <= '10/17/2021')]
        confirmed_covidData = confirmed_covidData.iloc[:, [0] + [1] + [3]]
        self.cases = confirmed_covidData.groupby(['Date','COUNTY'])['Cases'].aggregate('first').unstack()
        self.cases.index.name=''
        self.cases.columns.name=''
        #self.cases = self.cases[counties]
        
    def loadMobilityData(self, mobilityFile):
        """
         Function to load the mobility data for the different counties from an input file. Note that there are 
         several types of mobility modes in the raw data, including driving, walking, and transit. You may store 
         the data for each mobility mode separately as pandas DataFrame objects. The row in each dataframe object
         corresponds to a day and the columns are the different counties. You should only store the mobility
         data for the dates between March 1, 2020 to October 17, 2021 (columns 55 to 650). Note that the same
         county name may appear in more than 1 state (e.g., Wayne county). Therefore, make sure you select only
         the rows where the sub-region column value is Michigan. Furthermore, note that some counties may have 
         only driving data, but not transit and walking.
        """    
        def loadTypeWiseMobility(data):
            data = data.drop(columns='transportation_type').T
            data.columns = data.iloc[0]
            data = data[1:]
            data.columns.name = ''
            data.columns = [i[:-7] for i in data.columns]
            data.index = pd.to_datetime(data.index)
            return data
        
        mobilityData = pd.read_csv(mobilityFile)
        mobilityData = mobilityData[mobilityData[mobilityData.columns[4]] == 'Michigan']
        mobilityData = mobilityData[mobilityData[mobilityData.columns[0]] != 'city']
        list_of_columns = []
        list_of_columns.append(1)
        list_of_columns.append(2)
        for i in range(54,650):
            list_of_columns.append(i)
        mobilityData = mobilityData[mobilityData.columns[list_of_columns]]
        driving_mobilityData = mobilityData[mobilityData[mobilityData.columns[1]] == 'driving']
        self.driving = loadTypeWiseMobility(driving_mobilityData)
        walking_mobilityData = mobilityData[mobilityData[mobilityData.columns[1]] == 'walking']
        self.walking = loadTypeWiseMobility(walking_mobilityData)
        transit_mobilityData = mobilityData[mobilityData[mobilityData.columns[1]] == 'transit']
        self.transit = loadTypeWiseMobility(transit_mobilityData)
    
    def loadWeatherData(self, weatherFile):
        """
         Function to load the weather data for the various counties from an input file. You need the names of  
         the weather station associated with each county (e.g., Lansing for Ingham County). You should store 
         only the weather data for the dates between March 1, 2020 to October 17, 2021. Note that there are 
         3 types of weather variables (precipitation, maximum daily temperature, and minimum daily 
         temperature). You may store each weather variable separately as pandas dataframe objects. The row
         in each dataframe object corresponds to a day and the columns are the different counties.
        """
        def loadTypeWiseWeather(data):
            data = data.groupby([data.columns[1],data.columns[0]])[data.columns[2]].aggregate('first').unstack()
            data.index.name=''
            data.columns.name=''
            return data 
        
        weatherData = pd.read_csv(weatherFile)
        weatherData['DATE'] = pd.to_datetime(weatherData['DATE'], format="%m/%d/%Y")
        weatherData = weatherData.loc[(weatherData['DATE'] >= '3/1/2020') & (weatherData['DATE'] <= '10/17/2021')]
        weatherData = pd.merge(locations,weatherData,left_on=['STATION'],right_on=['NAME']).drop(columns=['STATION_x','STATION_y','NAME'])
        prcp_weatherData = weatherData[weatherData.columns[[0,1,2]]]
        tmax_weatherData = weatherData[weatherData.columns[[0,1,3]]]
        tmin_weatherData = weatherData[weatherData.columns[[0,1,4]]]
        self.prec = loadTypeWiseWeather(prcp_weatherData)
        self.tmax = loadTypeWiseWeather(tmax_weatherData)
        self.tmin = loadTypeWiseWeather(tmin_weatherData)        
                
    def getData(self, county):
        """
         Function to retrieve the data for a given county. The function will take a county name as input and will
         return a matrix of size N x 6, where  N = 596 corresponds to the different dates (from March 1, 2020 to 
         Oct 17, 2021) and the 6 columns correspond to the time series values of (driving, walking, transit, 
         precipitation, maximum temperature, and minimum temperature) for the given county. The matrix can be 
         stored either as a pandas DataFrame or a 2-dimensional numpy array object. In addition, the function 
         will also return a vector of size N = 596, corresponding to the number of covid-19 cases for the county.
         The vector can be stored as a pandas Series object or a 1-dimensional numpy array.
        """
        data = pd.DataFrame()
        if county in self.driving.columns:
            data['Driving'] = self.driving[county]
        if county in self.walking.columns:
            data['Walking'] = self.walking[county]
        if county in self.transit.columns:
            data['Transit'] = self.transit[county]
        if county in self.prec.columns:
            data['Precipitation'] = self.prec[county]
        if county in self.tmax.columns:
            data['Tmax'] = self.tmax[county]
        if county in self.tmin.columns:
            data['Tmin'] = self.tmin[county]
        cases_data = self.cases[county].to_numpy()
        return data,cases_data

Major takeaways from the above exploratory analysis are -

1) Out of 83 counties in Michigan, only few counties like Oakland, Wayne, Macomb, Kent are hotspot clusters for covid-19.

2) From the timeseries analysis and scatter plots, we can conculde that more cases have been reported during the winters( Less Tmin and Tmax).

3) Weather, mobility and cases of any county are weakly related.

4) Removal of outliers will result in loss of important information,thus affecting prediction models.

Moving Average

In [15]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

def movingAverage(data, interval, agg='mean'):
    cols = data.columns
    df = pd.DataFrame(columns=cols,index=data.index)
    for i in cols:
        l = data[i]
        j = 0
        avg = []
        if agg == 'mean':
            while j < len(l) - interval + 1:
                current_window = l[j :j + interval ]
                mov_avg = sum(current_window)/interval
                avg.append(mov_avg)
                j+=1
        if agg == 'sum':
            while j < len(l) - interval + 1:
                current_window = l[j :j + interval ]
                mov_avg = sum(current_window)
                avg.append(mov_avg)
                j+=1  
        if interval == 7:
            avg = [np.nan,np.nan,np.nan,np.nan,np.nan,np.nan]+avg
        if interval == 5:
            avg = [np.nan,np.nan,np.nan,np.nan]+avg
        if interval == 3:
            avg = [np.nan,np.nan]+avg
        df[i] = avg
    return df

GMM Model to cluster Covid-19 Data

from scipy.stats import multivariate_normal
from sklearn import cluster
import math

class GMM:
    def __init__(self, data):
        """
         A constructor function to initialize the state of the object. You will need to store the dataset to
         be clustered. 
        """ 
        return
        
        
    
    def fit(self,data,numClusters=3, maxiter=50):
        """
         This function takes the number of clusters and maximum number of iterations to cluster the data.
         The function will initialize the values for the mean vector, covariance matrix, and 
         membership value (pi) for each cluster before iteratively updating them using EM algorithm. You may
         apply methods such as k-means to cluster the data first and then use the cluster labels to compute
         the initial values for the mean vector, covariance matrix, and membership value (pi). The function 
         should return a vector that contains the cluster membership of each data point.
        """
        def calculate_LL(data,Q,Pi,Mu,Sigma):
            N,K = Q.shape
            s = 0
            for n in range(N):
                for k in range(K):
                    s += Q[n,k]*math.log(Pi[k])
                    s += Q[n,k]*multivariate_normal.logpdf(data[n], mean=Mu[:,k],cov=Sigma[k], allow_singular=True)
            return s
        
            
        rows,cols = data.shape
        Z = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=0).fit_predict(data)
        Q = np.zeros((rows, numClusters))
        Q[np.arange(rows),Z] = 1
        flag = False
        j = 0
        while j <= maxiter:
            sum_q = np.sum(Q, axis=0)
            Pi = sum_q/rows
            Mu = np.dot(data.T,Q)/sum_q
            Sigma = np.zeros((numClusters,cols,cols))
            for i in range(numClusters):
                for n in range(rows):
                    data_mu = np.reshape(data[n]-Mu[:,i],(cols,1))
                    Sigma[i] += Q[n,i]*np.dot(data_mu,data_mu.T)
                Sigma[i] /= sum_q[i]
            if not flag:
                Loglikelihood = calculate_LL(data,Q,Pi,Mu,Sigma)
                flag = True
            else:
                previousLL = Loglikelihood
                Loglikelihood = calculate_LL(data,Q,Pi,Mu,Sigma)
                if (math.fabs(Loglikelihood-previousLL) < 1e-1):
                    break
            for n in range(rows):
                for i in range(numClusters):
                    prob = multivariate_normal.pdf(data[n], mean=Mu[:,i], cov=Sigma[i],allow_singular=True)
                    Q[n,i] = Pi[i]*prob
                Q[n] /= np.sum(Q[n])
        return Q
        
    
    

    def display(self, clusters, county_names):
        """
         This function takes the clustering results and display the names of counties associated with each cluster.
        """ 
        cluster_1,cluster_2,cluster_3 = [],[],[]
        for i in range(len(clusters)):
            if clusters[i] == 0:
                cluster_1.append(county_names[i])
            elif clusters[i] == 1:
                cluster_2.append(county_names[i])
            else:
                cluster_3.append(county_names[i])
        print("Counties in cluster 1 - ", cluster_1)
        print("\nCounties in cluster 2 - ", cluster_2)
        print("\nCounties in cluster 3 - ", cluster_3)

def QR_GS(A):
    Q = A.copy()
    R = np.zeros(A.shape)
    Q[:,0] = Q[:,0]/np.linalg.norm(Q[:,0])
    R[0,0] = np.dot(A[:,0].T,Q[:,0])
    for i in range(1,A.shape[1]):
        for j in range(i):
            R[j,i] = np.dot(A[:,i].T,Q[:,j])
            Q[:,i] = Q[:,i] - R[j,i]*Q[:,j]
        Q[:,i] = Q[:,i]/np.linalg.norm(Q[:,i])
        R[i,i] = np.dot(A[:,i].T,Q[:,i])
    return (Q, R)

def QR_GR(A):
    Q = np.eye(A.shape[1])
    R = A.copy()
    for j in range(A.shape[1]-1):
        for i in range(A.shape[0]-1,j,-1):
            s = -R[i,j]/np.sqrt(R[i,j]**2+R[i-1,j]**2)
            c = R[i-1,j]/np.sqrt(R[i,j]**2+R[i-1,j]**2)
            G = np.eye(A.shape[1])
            G[i-1,i-1] = c
            G[i-1,i] = -s
            G[i,i-1] = s
            G[i,i] = c
            Q = np.matmul(Q,G.T)
            R = np.matmul(G,R)
        
    return (Q, R)
In [22]:
def backsubstitution(U, b):
    m, n = U.shape
        
    for i in range(n-1,-1,-1):
        if U[i,i] == 0:
            b[i] = 0
        else:
            b[i] = b[i]/U[i,i]
            for j in range(i+1, n):
                b[i] -= U[i,j] * b[j] / U[i,i]
    return b
In [23]:
def mlr_train(Xtrain, Ytrain,method="QR_GS"):
    
    A = np.dot(Xtrain.T, Xtrain)
    b = np.dot(Xtrain.T, Ytrain)
    if method=='QR_GS':
        print('QR using Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization')
        [Q,R] = QR_GS(A)
    else:
        print('QR using Givens rotation')
        [Q,R] = QR_GR(A)
    b = np.dot(Q.T, b)
    return backsubstitution(R,b)

def getCountyData(county):
    df,y = rawdata.getData(county)
    df['Cases'] = y
    mvg_cases_7 = movingAverage(rawdata.cases,7,"mean")
    mvg_cases_7.fillna(0,inplace=True)
    mvg_cases_5 = movingAverage(rawdata.cases,5,"mean")
    mvg_cases_5.fillna(0,inplace=True)
    mvg_cases_3 = movingAverage(rawdata.cases,3,"mean")
    mvg_cases_3.fillna(0,inplace=True)
    df['Mvg_Cases_7'] = mvg_cases_7[county]
    df['Mvg_Cases_5'] = mvg_cases_5[county]
    df['Mvg_Cases_3'] = mvg_cases_3[county]
    day = []
    for i in range(len(df)):
        t = pd.Timestamp(df.index[i])
        day.append(t.day_of_week)
    df['Day'] = day
    df['Weekend'] = day
    df['Weekend'] = df['Weekend'].replace({1:0,2:0,3:0,4:0,5:1,6:1})
    df = standardize(df)
    df.dropna(inplace=True)
    return df
